result.execSummary:
The defendant Terence Q. Majors was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Terence Q. Majors is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Terence Q. Majors was found guilty of 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Repeater], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.  This applies to all counts and financial obligations.

Obey all of the rules and regulations of supervising probation agent.
*  Pay supervision fees.
Do not possess or consume alcoholic beverages and do not have alcoholic beverages within the residence.  Do not be in taverns or on any premises licensed for the sale of intoxicating beverages, except restaurants or grocery stores.  Do not possess or consume controlled substances, except by prescription.  Submit voluntarily to random tests of blood, breath or urine.  Participate in counseling deemed appropriate by your agent, which may include: alcohol/drug, anger management/DV counseling, psychiatric/psychological, AODA Assessment and follow-through with recommended treatment.
*  Pay all court costs including all applicable surcharges.
*  If unpaid financial obligations remain at discharge or revocation, civil judgment to be entered.
*  Pay DNA surcharge  $250.00
*  Pay resitution plus surcharges; the State shall have 60 days to determine restitution.
May not have contact with Ondrea Hoaglund or her residence, unless otherwise permitted by the court/agent.

records.addlTxt: Order to Extend Probation

8:25 AM Prosecuting attorney Daniel Joseph Tombasco in court for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant Terence Q. Majors in court, in custody. Probation Agent Christine Munger appeared by video.  Clerk N. Nobile.
MINUTES: Agent Munger advises the Court that the DE has not made any payments towards restitution. DE advises the Court that he was unaware of the restitution owed in this case and only knew about the restitution owed in his Racine Case. Based on the DE's failure to pay restitution, Court extends probation for a period of 1 year from 11/05/2022 to 11/05/2023. Probation may be terminated early if the restitution amount is paid in full. Court will prepare order.
